<br>
The other day, playing as a rogue, I was given a quest to procure a few assorted items from about one of the cities in the game. <br>
<br>
So, I wandered into a specific district and cased the immediate area about the house, noting the local guard patrols and the private estate guard outside of the house I needed to get into. <br>
<br>
I waited for the patrol to go by, went into stealth mode, and snuck in behind the stationary guard. I picked the lock, opened the door, crept through, and closed the door behind me, laughing all the while as I realized the guard was oblivious to my presence. <br>
<br>
Once inside, I dashed for another shadowy corner, and waited until I saw a guard patrol go by. <br>
<br>
*knew there had to be one* <br>
<br>
Once he went by, I counted until I saw him come around again to get a sense of his cycle. And by he went, and out into the hall I dashed. <br>
<br>
Quickly, I spotted a few traps laying on the ground and I set to recovering each of them as I continued the count in my head. And, once recovering them, I set about to laying them down again in new areas, turning them against the guards they were to have assisted. <br>
<br>
And then, once again, I dashed for another doorway, as the guard came by, only slightly off his count. <br>
<br>
The patrolman sprung the trap and died. Muhuhuhaha. That was fun. It served no real purpose. He was easy enough to avoid. But I was feeling evil. <br>
<br>
But now I wondered if other guards would notice the lack of a patrol and sound the alarm. Not wanting to wait around to find out, I dashed about the estate, intent on finding the owner. <br>
<br>
I snuck past a few patrols here and there, picking locks, opening and closing doors (and the occasional chest), all while in stealth mode. <br>
<br>
Finally, I found my mark: standing alone in his bedroom was a nervous-looking noble. I left stealth mode and imagined that the fellow must have lost control of himself as he saw a well-armed man casually walk into the room from out of nowhere. <br>
<br>
I threatened him verbally, and told him I was here to take something specific. I could have just taken it, but this was so much more fun. Unfortunately, there was a bug in the game! The item wasn't placed. Grrr! <br>
<br>
So I tore out of the room, went into stealth mode, snuck back into the noble's room, and hit him for about 47 points of damage. I doubt he had more than 3 hit points. Poor fellow. <br>
<br>
Leaving, I knew the guards would be aware of me now, and they were. Guard patrols were all over the place, but easy enough to avoid or sneak past. <br>
<br>
Near the end, I found a few guards waiting by the door. I left stealth mode from my poisition behind a few of those old remaining traps. The guards charged, and died before they even reached me. Ahhh... <br>
<br>
I slipped out the door, and initiated dialogue with the lone estate guard. &quot;You can't come in. No one gets in.&quot;, or something like that, he said. I replied that was no problem, and that I'd be on my way... <br>
<br>
Ah, such is the life of the rogue in Neverwinter Nights. <br>
